Outliers¶

  • We calculate skewness of each column using skew() function.
  • The skewness of each of our columns is zero / 0.
  • That is, we can say that 0 indicates that the distribution is perfectly symmetric.
  • And, there are no outliers in our data.

# 'gross income' distribution

plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
sns.histplot(df['gross income'])
plt.axvline(x=np.mean(df['gross income']), c='white',ls='--', label='mean')
plt.axvline(x=np.percentile(df['gross income'], 25), c='white',ls='--', label='25th - 75th percentile')
plt.axvline(x=np.percentile(df['gross income'], 75), c='white',ls='--', label='25th - 75th percentile')
plt.title('Gross Income')
plt.legend()
plt.savefig('grossinc.png')
plt.show()

Sales Trends¶

In [125]:
grouped_data = df.groupby('Date').agg({'Unit price': 'sum', 'Quantity': 'sum', 'Total': 'sum'})

# Plot sales trends over time
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,6))
grouped_data.plot(ax=ax)
ax.set_xlabel('Date')
ax.set_ylabel('Sales')
ax.set_title('Sales Trends')
plt.show()

percentage of total ratings for each rating¶

In [126]:
# percentage of total ratings for each rating

rating_percentages = df['Rating'].value_counts() / df['Rating'].sum() * 100

# rating percentages bar chart
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(18,6))
rating_percentages.plot(kind='bar', ax=ax)
plt.xlabel('Ratings', fontsize=18, color='green')
plt.title('Rating percentage', fontsize=20, color='green')
plt.savefig('rating.png')
plt.show()
